\begin_layout Subsection
A quick aside on how to cheat at dice
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before moving on, let's pause to make sure we understand what 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\epsdice{6}}$
\end_inset

 means.
 (This will come in handy later).
 When we roll a dice, it can come up in one of six ways.
 With this in mind, a very general way to write 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\epsdice{6}}$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{\epsdice{6}}=\frac{w_{6}}{\sum_{i=1}^{i\le6}w_{i}}\label{eq:psix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
weight 
\emph default
given to a face on the dice.
 The sum on the bottom (
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{i\le6}w_{i}$
\end_inset

) is the 
\emph on
normalization factor
\emph default
.
 It describes the total the likelihood of a roll giving
\emph on
 
\emph default
all faces, allowing us to determine the relative probability of each specific
 face.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a dice is fair, all faces have the same weight:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{\epsdice{6}}=\frac{1}{1+1+1+1+1+1}=\frac{1}{6}\approx0.167
\]

\end_inset

Note we could assign any weight we wanted, as long as it was the same for
 all faces:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{\epsdice{6}}=\frac{0.001}{0.001+0.001+0.001+0.001+0.001+0.001}=\frac{0.001}{0.006}\approx0.167
\]

\end_inset

If we want to bias our results to get more 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

, we could put more weight on that face.
 What if put a weight of 10 on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 face, while setting the weight on every other face to 1? 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{\epsdice{6}}=\frac{10}{1+1+1+1+1+10}=\frac{10}{15}\approx0.667
\]

\end_inset

We could even imagine an exotic dice where every face had a different weight.
 For example, imagine a dice weighted such that every face had the same
 weight as its numerical value.
 In that case: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{\epsdice{6}}=\frac{6}{1+2+3+4+5+6}=\frac{6}{21}\approx0.286
\]

\end_inset

Finally, if we want to know the probability of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{1}$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
or 
\emph default
a 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

, we could write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{\epsdice{1}}+p_{\epsdice{6}}=\frac{w_{1}}{\sum_{i=1}^{i\le6}w_{i}}+\frac{w_{6}}{\sum_{i=1}^{i\le6}w_{i}}=\frac{w_{1}+w_{6}}{\sum_{i=1}^{i\le6}w_{i}}
\]

\end_inset

We can summarize our brief tangent as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Weights 
\emph default
can be any (positive) number for each face.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
To convert weight to probaility, we divide by sum of weights on all sides.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
To get the probability of face 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 or face 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset


\series default
, calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{a}+w_{b}$
\end_inset

 over the sum of the weights on all sides.
 
\end_layout

