\begin_layout Standard
We can make a couple of observations from these simulations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Reactions become more predictable as the number of molecules increases.

\series default
 As the number of dice increase, the curves become smoother.
 Hopefully, this is intuitive.
 Because dice rolling is a random process, it takes a large number of dice
 to average out all of the fluctuations.
 When we have only 
\begin_inset Formula $20$
\end_inset

 dice, the fraction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 fluctuates up and down because even one low-probability roll has a huge
 effect on the outcome.
 When we have 
\begin_inset Formula $2,000$
\end_inset

 dice, the fraction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 is robust to a few low probability events, simply because there are so
 many dice that we average over.
 In chemical reactions, we usually have millions and millions of molecules,
 making the reaction dynamics quite predictably.
 (Intriguingly, this is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
always true in a cell, were the number of reactants can sometimes involve
 only tens of molecules.
 A cell might have only ten copies of a transcription factor.
 This leads to 
\emph on
cellular noise
\emph default
—a fascinating topic we will not cover, but that is worth reading about).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Reactions converge to equilibrium whatever their starting conditions.

\series default
 No matter how many 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

