\begin_layout Section
A kinetic explanation for convergence to equilibrium:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One way to think about why this reaction converges is to consider the rates
 of the forward and reverse reactions (Fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:roll-convergence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Imagine we start with a collection of dice that are all 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

.
 At each step, we pick up a single dice and roll it.
 For the first step, we can only pick up 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

; when we roll it, there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $5/6$
\end_inset

 chance we end up with something besides 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

.
 This means that the most probable outcome of that first roll is to lower
 the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 (Fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:roll-convergence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 For the first few rolls, we will still have more 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 than other numbers, so we will continue to favor rolls that lower the number
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

.
 As we continue to roll dice, however, the number of non-
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 dice will increase, eventually allowing transitions from non-
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 back to 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, after enough time, the rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 loss and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 gain offset offset, leading to the equilibrium value of 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\epsdice{6}}$
\end_inset

.
