status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Or at least that we made the same mistake in both places! 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have a rate law, we can ask about the equilibrium state of the
 reaction.
 What happens as 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

? If we substitute in 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

, we find:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{\epsdice{6}}=p_{\epsdice{6}}N\left(1-e^{-\infty}\right)+N_{\epsdice{6},0}e^{-\infty}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{\epsdice{6}}=p_{\epsdice{6}}N
\]

\end_inset

After infinite time, we've the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 is given by the probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 times the total number of dice.
 When our dice reach this special concentration, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\epsdice{6}}N$
\end_inset

, the rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 formation precisely offsets the rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

, leading to this equilbrium value.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Link to biochemistry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So how do these models for dice relate to real chemistry? In a chemistry
 text book, you'll find that a first-order rate constant looks something
 like this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d[product]}{dt}=k\cdot[reactant]
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
rate constant
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $[product]$
\end_inset

 is the concentration of product and 
\begin_inset Formula $[reactant]$
\end_inset

 is the concentration of reactant.
 It turns out, we already wrote discrete versions of this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{N_{other\rightarrow\epsdice{6}}}{\Delta t}=\alpha\cdot\left(N-N_{\epsdice{6}}\right)\cdot p_{\epsdice{6}}.
\]

\end_inset

In our discrete system with unimolecular reactions, 
\begin_inset Formula $N-N_{\epsdice{6}}$
\end_inset

 is operating like a concentration (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how many non-
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 are available to react?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 This means that the rate constant for the reaction is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{other\rightarrow\epsdice{6}}=\alpha\cdot p_{\epsdice{6}}.
\]

\end_inset

Our rate constant has two basic chunks: how many tries you make per turn
 (remember, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is the fraction of the dice we pick up and roll on a turn) and the probability
 a reaction occurs per try (
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\epsdice{6}}$
\end_inset

).
 We will revisit it when we discuss the 
\emph on
Arrhenius equation
\emph default
.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To whet your appetite, you may have seen:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k=A\cdot e^{-E^{\ddagger}/RT}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a prefactor that controls how often a reaction samples (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tries to cross
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) an energy barrier.
 This is analogous to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 The other term, 
\begin_inset Formula $exp(-E^{\ddagger}/RT)$
\end_inset

, is the probability the reaction crosses a barrier of height 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{\ddagger}$
\end_inset

 at temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 This is analogous to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\epsdice{6}}$
\end_inset

.
 This is a rough, as we are not discussing an energy barrier for our dice.
 But the basic formulation of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how often do you try?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 times 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how probable you are at succeeding?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 occurs all over in chemical kinetics.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How about equilibrium constants? Can we understand what they mean in terms
 of the dice reaction? You have probably seen that, for a two-state reaction,
 you can write:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{eq}=\frac{k_{forward}}{k_{reverse}}
\]

\end_inset

We already have 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{forward}$
\end_inset

 from above (
\begin_inset Formula $k_{other\rightarrow\epsdice{6}}$
\end_inset

).
 By analogy:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{reverse}=k_{\epsdice{6}\rightarrow other}=\alpha\cdot\left(1-p_{\epsdice{6}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

If we substitute this into the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{eq}$
\end_inset

 above, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{k_{forward}}{k_{reverse}}=\frac{\cancel{\alpha}p_{\epsdice{6}}}{\cancel{\alpha}(1-p_{\epsdice{6}})}=\frac{p_{\epsdice{6}}}{1-p_{\epsdice{6}}}.
\]

\end_inset

You have also probably seen that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{eq}=\frac{[products]}{[reactants]}.
\]

\end_inset

Can we get there with the DFR? From our rate law, we found that the final
 concentration of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 was 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\epsdice{6}}N$
\end_inset

.
 If we substitute this into our equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{eq}$
\end_inset

 above, we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{eq}=\frac{N_{\epsdice{6}}}{N-N_{\epsdice{6}}}=\frac{p_{\epsdice{6}}N}{N-p_{\epsdice{6}}N}=\frac{p_{\epsdice{6}}}{1-p_{\epsdice{6}}}.
\]

\end_inset

Hopefully from this quick analysis you can see better what first-order rate
 constants and equilibrium constants mean.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 (first-order rate constant): How often one tries a reaction times the probabili
ty the reaction occurs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $K_{eq}=\frac{k_{forward}}{k_{reverse}}=\frac{[products]}{[reactants]}$
\end_inset

