\begin_layout Standard
A second way to understand the directionality of these reactions is by thinking
 about the relative probability of different arrangements of dice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We'll start with a simple, preliminary argument.
 Imagine we start with a collection of random dice and start rolling.
 What's the probability we end up with all 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 at some point? Hopefully it is intuitive that there are many more ways
 to be something besides all 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 than to be all 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

.
 If we have two dice, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 possibilities for the first dice, and 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 possibilities for the second dice.
 This means we have 
\begin_inset Formula $6\times6=36$
\end_inset

 different ways to arrange the dice.
 Since there is only one way to get 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

, the probability of seeing 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/36\approx0.03$
\end_inset

.
 The scaling relationship for the number of possible arrangements of the
 dice goes by 
\begin_inset Formula $6^{N_{dice}}$
\end_inset

.
 This means that even for four dice, there is only a 
\begin_inset Formula $1/1,296$
\end_inset

 chance of getting four 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 by chance.
 By the time we hit 
\begin_inset Formula $100$
\end_inset

 dice, the odds of getting 
\begin_inset Formula $100\ \epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 are absurdly low: 
\begin_inset Formula $1.5\times10^{-78}$
\end_inset

.
 
