 To get that, we're going to need to recall two basic rules from probability:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
ANDs MULTIPLY.
 If you have two independent events—like rolling 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 on one dice AND rolling 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{1}$
\end_inset

 on a second dice—the probability of both events occuring is the 
\emph on
product
\emph default
 of the probabilities of each independent event (
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\epsdice{6}}\times p_{\epsdice{1}}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
ORs ADD.
 If you have two mutually exclusive events—like rolling a 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 OR rolling a 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{1}$
\end_inset

 on the same dice—the probability of seeing one or the other is the 
\emph on
sum 
\emph default
of the two probabilities (
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\epsdice{6}}+p_{\epsdice{1}}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's develop our formula by asking what the probability of seeing exactly
 one 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 when rolling three dice is.
 We could roll 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 first and then roll something besides 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 twice.
 Since the dice are independent, the probability of this series of events
 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{\epsdice{6}}\times(1-p_{\epsdice{6}})\times(1-p_{\epsdice{6}}).
\]

\end_inset

We could also roll something beside 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 first, roll 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 second, and then roll something beside 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 third:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1-p_{\epsdice{6}})\times p_{\epsdice{6}}\times(1-p_{\epsdice{6}}).
\]

\end_inset

Or, finally, we could roll something beside 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 twice and then roll 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 third:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1-p_{\epsdice{6}})\times(1-p_{\epsdice{6}})\times p_{\epsdice{6}}.
\]

\end_inset

These series of events are mutually exclusive: if we only saw one 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 in three rolls, we either saw the 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 first, second, or third.
 The total probability of seeing one 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

 is thus the sum of the probabilities of these exclusive series of events:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{one\times\epsdice{6}}=p_{\epsdice{6}}\times(1-p_{\epsdice{6}})\times(1-p_{\epsdice{6}})+(1-p_{\epsdice{6}})\times p_{\epsdice{6}}\times(1-p_{\epsdice{6}})+(1-p_{\epsdice{6}})\times(1-p_{\epsdice{6}})\times p_{\epsdice{6}}.
\]

\end_inset

We can factor and rearrange to yield:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{one\times\epsdice{6}}=3\times p_{\epsdice{6}}^{1}\left(1-p_{\epsdice{6}}\right)^{2}
\]

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in this equation is called the 
\emph on
multiplicity
\emph default
.
 It describes how many different ways we could achieve one 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

—in this case, three.
 We raise 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\epsdice{6}}$
\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{st}$
\end_inset

 power because we see it once, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-p_{\epsdice{6}})$
\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{nd}$
\end_inset

 power because we see it twice.
 
\end_layout

