\begin_inset Formula $k=k_{1}$
\end_inset

 state.
 The ratio of these two probabilities is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{P(n,k_{2})}{P(n,k_{1})}=\text{\ensuremath{\frac{\binom{n}{k_{2}}p^{k_{2}}\left(1-p\right)^{n-k_{2}}}{\binom{n}{k_{1}}p^{k_{1}}(1-p)^{n-k_{1}}}}}
\]

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{n}{k_{1}}$
\end_inset

 notation is a bit unwieldly, so let's replace it with a 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{k}$
\end_inset

, which will still represent the number of arragements that are possible
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsdice{6}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{k}=\binom{n}{k}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{P(n,k_{2})}{P(n,k_{1})}=\text{\ensuremath{\frac{W_{k_{2}}p^{k_{2}}\left(1-p\right)^{n-k_{2}}}{W_{k_{1}}p^{k_{1}}(1-p)^{n-k_{1}}}}}
\]

\end_inset

To make things simpler, let's take the 
\begin_inset Formula $-ln$
\end_inset

 of both sides.
 (This makes it way easier to deal with a probability like 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-234}$
\end_inset

 because: 
\begin_inset Formula $-ln\left(10^{-234}\right)=234ln(10)=538.8$
\end_inset

.)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-ln\left[\frac{P(n,k_{2})}{P(n,k_{1})}\right]=-ln\left[\text{\ensuremath{\frac{W_{k_{2}}p^{k_{2}}\left(1-p\right)^{n-k_{2}}}{W_{k_{1}}p^{k_{1}}(1-p)^{n-k_{1}}}}}\right]
\]

\end_inset

Because 
\begin_inset Formula $log(a\cdot b)=log(a)+log(b)$
\end_inset

